data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent. The key mappings are:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

```csharp
// Fixture class handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // was [OneTimeSetUp]
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // was [OneTimeTearDown]
    }
}

// Constructor/Dispose replace [SetUp]/[TearDown]
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();       // was [SetUp]
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();                  // was [TearDown]
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key changes:
- **`IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>`** — xUnit creates one `DatabaseFixture` instance shared across all tests in the class, replacing `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`.
- **Constructor/`IDisposable`** — xUnit creates a new class instance per test, so the constructor replaces `[SetUp]` and `Dispose` replaces `[TearDown]`.
- **Assertions** — `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` → `Assert.NotNull(x)`, `Is.EqualTo` → `Assert.Equal`.
